	<p>And most importantly <strong>being open</strong>, in three different ways. Being open about our practice, which is itself the process of being open to our experience.</p><br>

	<p>Being open about meditation itself - talking honestly about benefits, states, and stages without fear of impinging upon taboo or dogma. We want to break open meditation itself, a millenia old tradition with extraordinary potential that has historically been distorted through religious and spiritual beliefs. We want to help distill its potent essence and make it available to anyone who is willing to give it a few minutes a day.</p><br>
	<p>But we don't just talk the talk - OpenSit is itself an experiment in openness. It is completely open source. That means anyone can view the code behind it and help out. We believe transparency builds trust and we want you to help build our community and have a say in its direction.</p>

	<h2>Our Goals</h2>
	<ul>
		<li>To <strong>establish free community for people to share their meditation practice</strong>, and longer term develop a more sophisticated contemplative expression platform that will innovate in the ways we share, understand and teach meditation practice.</li>
		<li>To <strong>publish content</strong> that inspires others to try meditation, and that furthers the global understanding and impact of meditation.</li>
		<li>To encourage <strong>a pragmatic, DIY approach to meditation</strong>, that emphasises transparency and practice over dogma or tradition, and a spirit of adventure and mutual support over fantasy or fashion. Journals in particular help demystify meditation.</li>
	</ul>

